Message:By the way, I've found a tutorial for making the elven brooches, and it's TOTALLY doable. Basically if you use very thin sheet metal (or even metal from aluminum cans) it doesn't require special tools and you can create the raised veins of the leaf by pressing on the back with a pen. I probably own most of the tools, and at least some of the necessary materials. Jordan Preuss
ID:512808080_10152184753673081
Name:null
Story:N/A
Message:Happy Birthday!!! Since you are now twenty-four years old, enjoy some facts about the number 24, courtesy of wikipedia:

The product of any four consecutive integers must be divisible by 24, because two of the numbers must be even, one must be divisible by four, and one must be divisible by three.

24 is the atomic number of chromium.

There are 24 spokes on the Ashoka Chakra, which appears on the Indian flag. 

24 is the number of blackbirds baked in a pie in the English nursery rhyme Sing a Sing of Sixpence.

Message:Does there happen to be a guy around here who is coming back to Chapel Hill next year and is still looking for a place to live? They're looking for one more male student for the 2013-2014 academic year, and if you're interested you can contact Walker Mabe at wmabe@thechapelofthecross.org.

I have already reserved a room and talked to three speakers from the IX Network and Huff Post who will be flying in to be on the event's panel.
What I need help with is primarily outreach, pubbing, and contacting local speakers to join the panel. If you are interested in education rights, college administration and policy, and/or interpersonal violence, please contact me. Knowledge of Title IX law is not necessary, but would be helpful if you would like to help in the planning of the event. Thanks!

ID:546078416_10152537532588417
Name:null
Story:N/A
Message:Hi friends! Brittany and Sarah here- we are so excited for Friday that we wanted to start the collaborative poetry circle early! See the prompt* below for creating this digital poem and make comments on this post to add new lines:

*The following poetic exercise is taken from the book, Electronic Corpse: Poems from a Digital Salon, edited by M. Ayodele Heath. 

The rules: 

1. We will provide one line from an existing poem as a 1st line for the new poem. Anyone can add new lines to the poem by commenting on this post. 

2. The new poem we are composing will use ANAPHORA, a repetition of a word/phrase at the beginning of successive clauses/verses. In this case, the word/phrase beginning each line will be ?Hope is?. 

3. You can add more than one line, but you cannot add lines consecutively. (For example, if you add the 3rd line, you can?t also add the 4th. Someone else has to take a turn before you can go again.)

4. The poem will be 18 lines.

5. Happy writing!

First line: Hope is a bird?s wing
Source of First Line: Pauli Murray?s ?Dark Testament: Verse 8? 

Barbara Lau Dolores Chandler Zoe Caves Justin Ching Pablo Finnamore  Mendal Polish Mars Earle Dylan Su-Chun Mott Jeanette Stokes Ashe Danger Phoenix Kimberly Redefining Freedom McCrae Cameron Bynum Victoria Petermann Hannah Cerene Tobin

Logan Cerwin takes 6th in the open category (youngest athlete in the category), and Gil Cukierman shakes things up with a 5th in perhaps the strongest open field anywhere including national and world champions (and 2nd youngest in the category). Locally, TMS-IOS team member Robert VanGraafeiland takes another victory at the Smile Train Triathlon.

Congrats to all!

Message:I've been tagged by Wendy Lu and Catie Hill to list my favorite book, so here they are in (rough) order, with 1 being the most favorite:

1. "The English Patient" by Michael Ondaatje-- the greatest book ever written by a human!
2. "In the Skin of a Lion" by Michael Ondaatje
3. "Divisadero" by Michael Ondaatje
4. "The Satanic Verses" by Salman Rushdie
5. "Shalimar the Clown" by Salman Rushdie
6. "Coriolanus" by William Shakespeare-- do plays count? Fuck it, this is my list!
7. "Julius Caesar" by William Shakespeare
8. "The Enchantress of Florence" by Salman Rushdie
9. "Anil's Ghost" by Michael Ondaatje
10. "Paradise Lost" by John Milton
11. "Much Ado About Nothing" by William Shakespeare
12. "Como Agua Para Chocolate" por Laura Esquivel
13. "Les Miserables" by Victor Hugo-- sadly, I have only read this in English
14. "The Handmaid's Tale" by Margaret Atwood
15. "The Martian Chronicles" by Ray Bradbury

ID:708705302_10152032127220303
Name:null
Story:N/A
Message:Today i walked into Teague and saw all the empty rooms and halls. I felt empty. Today was graduation. It's suppose to be a happy day, but somehow i felt sad.   I walked out of the global center after the econ commencement in a hurry without really saying good byes to my friends because i was tired. I didnt realize that this is one of the last few moments we will have together. In a couple of days, we would all depart. Although we all say "keep in touch" and "visit each other often", the ugly truth is that we probably wont. Its not that we dont value our friendship. Its that we are now going into the real world to start our new life and family, and itll be hard to sit back, relax, and reconnect with our old friends from our busy lives.  Throughout these four years, i made some great friends; some with annoying qualities haha. But today, when its time to depart, all i see and remember are the good times we had together, because thats wut really matters.  This last senior year has been crazy. I had so much fun! Thanks guys for a great year! These are the best times i had on college. I really hope that these days can last forever where we just drink and play random games. Thanks guys! Im not gonna wish u guys good luck for ur post graduation lives because i know you guys wont need it. Im gonna wish for us to be able to come back and relive our days together soon! <3

Name:Board of Governors targets need-based aid programs
Story:N/A
Message:I normally do not post Student Government related things on my personal facebook, but this is really important for all Carolina students to pay attention to.

For a long time, Carolina has made a remarkable promise to our students: if you are talented enough to earn a spot in Chapel Hill, we will make sure you can afford to come here. We cannot break that promise if we are to remain the University of the People. Jeopardizing our commitment to meeting 100% of demonstrated need would be a terrible consequence of this policy proposal and deeply counterproductive to the Board's core goal of affordability.

Story:Matthew James Leming uploaded a new version of photos.zip in the group Computer Science.
Message:Hey all!
First, happy-snappy FDOC! Just brief FYIs here, as well as an overview of the doings for the semester:
? The first CS Club meeting is Wednesday, August 27th at 5:00 PM in FB 007. We'll be going over the hackerspace, HackNC, WICs (separate-but-affiliated), tutoring, and various other stuff that's happening this semester. Still trying to get the room reserved, but this will kind of probably be the way it goes.
? COMP 110/116/(401) Tutoring will happen in FB 007 from 5:00 to 7:00 starting on August 28th. Message rramkuma@live.unc.edu if you're interested in participating as a tutor this semester so he can get you on the listserv. This is a hugely informal process. If you're interested, just show up.
? HackNC (http://hacknc.us) meetings will be happening Wednesdays at 8:00 in the CS Club room. Email Vance Miller (v@unc.edu) for more information.
? Join our Facebook group: https://www.facebook.com/groups/unccsclub/
? Undergraduate Open House is early this year ? Tuesday, August 26th, at 5:00 PM in SN 014.
? Microsoft events are on Thursday, August 28th, 2014, 10:00 AM to 2:00 PM, and 6:30 PM (Resume Clinic) in the lower lobby. http://csclub.cs.unc.edu/Events/.
? More reliable GCal at http://www.cs.unc.edu/Events/Calendar/.
Additionally, Dr. Kevin Jeffay is the new head of the Computer Science Department! To celebrate, I would greatly appreciate it if everyone would go to http://yugico.com/yugioh-card-creator, photoshop Jeffay's head onto some image, create a Yu-Gi-Oh card out of it, and send the result to jeffay@cs.unc.edu with the subject line "Congratulations!". Head and example attached.
Thanks!

Message:Hey all!

First, happy-snappy FDOC! Just brief FYIs here, as well as an overview of the doings for the semester:

? The first CS Club meeting is Wednesday, August 27th at 5:00 PM in FB 007. We'll be going over the hackerspace, HackNC, WICs (separate-but-affiliated), tutoring, and various other stuff that's happening this semester. Still trying to get the room reserved, but this will kind of probably be the way it goes.
? COMP 110/116/(401) Tutoring will happen in FB 007 from 5:00 to 7:00 starting on August 28th. Message rramkuma@live.unc.edu if you're interested in participating as a tutor this semester so he can get you on the listserv. This is a hugely informal process. If you're interested, just show up.
? HackNC (http://hacknc.us) meetings will be happening Wednesdays at 8:00 in the CS Club room. Email Vance Miller (v@unc.edu) for more information.
? Join our Facebook group: https://www.facebook.com/groups/unccsclub/
? Undergraduate Open House is early this year ? Tuesday, August 26th, at 5:00 PM in SN 014.
? Microsoft events are on Thursday, August 28th, 2014, 10:00 AM to 2:00 PM, and 6:30 PM (Resume Clinic) in the lower lobby. http://csclub.cs.unc.edu/Events/.
? More reliable GCal at http://www.cs.unc.edu/Events/Calendar/.

Additionally, Dr. Kevin Jeffay is the new head of the Computer Science Department! To celebrate, I would greatly appreciate it if everyone would go to http://yugico.com/yugioh-card-creator, photoshop Jeffay's head onto some image, create a Yu-Gi-Oh card out of it, and send the result to jeffay@cs.unc.edu with the subject line "Congratulations!". Head and example attached.

Thanks!

Message:Loving every word of this article. Fantastic read on some of the issues within higher ed in the U.S., and hopefully how we can help change them.

"Our system of elite education manufactures young people who are smart and talented and driven, yes, but also anxious, timid, and lost, with little intellectual curiosity and a stunted sense of purpose: trapped in a bubble of privilege, heading meekly in the same direction, great at what they?re doing but with no idea why they?re doing it [...] 

This system is exacerbating inequality, retarding social mobility, perpetuating privilege, and creating an elite that is isolated from the society that it?s supposed to lead. "

Message:Hey all,

On behalf of the Adidas NC Open committee and NCSU Badminton club, we would like to thank all of you, players, spectators, sponsors, and especially the NCSU students, for your genuine and enthusiastic support.

We hope you all had a great time at the tournament!

Congratulations to 2 of our fellow NCSU players ( Noel Mathew and Sajeesh Kumar ) who came in 1st and 2nd in the Men's Singles division C event. 

We hope all the players who took park in the tournament had a great experience participating and meeting a lot of good players.

Thanks to all the NCSU volunteers who worked as line judges, ran the registration desk, court martials, organizing and raising the enthusiasm of the tournament. 

Special thanks to Yiwen Luo, Mayu Namba, Eileen Gu, Ji Zhao, Tianheng, Ying Liao  and others who put in a lot of hard work to make this event a success.

Hope you all enjoyed taking part in playing, watching, organizing and running the tournament!

Thanks a lot,
NC Open Committee

Story:N/A
Message:Yesterday, I was nominated for the ALS ice bucket challenge by my lovely friend Kaitlyn Kopala, but instead of dumping precious water on my head that I'm sure could be used for better things, I'd like to draw attention to some other note worthy causes that are close to my heart. There is the American Cancer Society (http://www.cancer.org) who raises money for cancer research because there isn't a person who hasn't been affected by cancer whether it be themselves, a family member, a colleague, or a friend. Then there is the Humane Society of the United States (http://www.humanesociety.org) which works to protect animals from abuse across the nation. And lastly, there are two local organizations to the Triangle that can always use more volunteers and donations: Carolina Tiger Rescue (http://www.carolinatigerrescue.org) and Miracle League of the Triangle (http://miracleleagueofthetriangle.com). So I nominate everyone who reads this to find a cause that you're passionate about and advocate for it.

ID:1531609000_10201669923259817
Name:null
Story:N/A
Message:Today i walked into Teague and saw all the empty rooms and halls. I felt empty. Today was graduation. It's suppose to be a happy day, but somehow i felt sad.   I walked out of the global center after the econ commencement in a hurry without really saying good byes to my friends because i was tired. I didnt realize that this is one of the last few moments we will have together. In a couple of days, we would all depart. Although we all say "keep in touch" and "visit each other often", the ugly truth is that we probably wont. Its not that we dont value our friendship. Its that we are now going into the real world to start our new life and family, and itll be hard to sit back, relax, and reconnect with our old friends from our busy lives.  Throughout these four years, i made some great friends; some with annoying qualities haha. But today, when its time to depart, all i see and remember are the good times we had together, because thats wut really matters.  This last senior year has been crazy. I had so much fun! Thanks guys for a great year! These are the best times i had on college. I really hope that these days can last forever where we just drink and play random games. Thanks guys! Im not gonna wish u guys good luck for ur post graduation lives because i know you guys wont need it. Im gonna wish for us to be able to come back and relive our days together soon! <3

ID:1550150680_10204230218386213
Name:Summer 2014
Story:N/A
Message:I played go (weiqi) for nine years before dropping it to spend more time on academics in high school. 

This summer, I've been playing at the Seattle Go Center and it's reminded me just how beautiful the game is. I got to know the player in this photo very well over some tough matches and it also turns out he's a visiting law professor from Tsinghua University in Beijing. I'll be studying abroad there this fall and he says he'll introduce me to some professional players in the city to help me improve both my Mandarin and go playing skills.

Goes to show that you can make valuable connections in the most unexpected of places! 

Photo creds to Einar Veizaga

ID:100000291936863_784277821591942
Name:null
Story:N/A
Message:Today i walked into Teague and saw all the empty rooms and halls. I felt empty. Today was graduation. It's suppose to be a happy day, but somehow i felt sad.   I walked out of the global center after the econ commencement in a hurry without really saying good byes to my friends because i was tired. I didnt realize that this is one of the last few moments we will have together. In a couple of days, we would all depart. Although we all say "keep in touch" and "visit each other often", the ugly truth is that we probably wont. Its not that we dont value our friendship. Its that we are now going into the real world to start our new life and family, and itll be hard to sit back, relax, and reconnect with our old friends from our busy lives.  Throughout these four years, i made some great friends; some with annoying qualities haha. But today, when its time to depart, all i see and remember are the good times we had together, because thats wut really matters.  This last senior year has been crazy. I had so much fun! Thanks guys for a great year! These are the best times i had on college. I really hope that these days can last forever where we just drink and play random games. Thanks guys! Im not gonna wish u guys good luck for ur post graduation lives because i know you guys wont need it. Im gonna wish for us to be able to come back and relive our days together soon! <3

ID:100001043113693_771080102936753
Name:null
Story:N/A
Message:Today i walked into Teague and saw all the empty rooms and halls. I felt empty. Today was graduation. It's suppose to be a happy day, but somehow i felt sad.   I walked out of the global center after the econ commencement in a hurry without really saying good byes to my friends because i was tired. I didnt realize that this is one of the last few moments we will have together. In a couple of days, we would all depart. Although we all say "keep in touch" and "visit each other often", the ugly truth is that we probably wont. Its not that we dont value our friendship. Its that we are now going into the real world to start our new life and family, and itll be hard to sit back, relax, and reconnect with our old friends from our busy lives.  Throughout these four years, i made some great friends; some with annoying qualities haha. But today, when its time to depart, all i see and remember are the good times we had together, because thats wut really matters.  This last senior year has been crazy. I had so much fun! Thanks guys for a great year! These are the best times i had on college. I really hope that these days can last forever where we just drink and play random games. Thanks guys! Im not gonna wish u guys good luck for ur post graduation lives because i know you guys wont need it. Im gonna wish for us to be able to come back and relive our days together soon! <3

Message:Sales & Marketing High School Representatives (Now Accepting Applications!)

To those who are now studying at U.S. high schools:
Are you interested in real-world business? Do you want to show your leadership skills through meaningful extracurricular experiences? Are you seeking ways to make a real impact on your community? Do you want to join a company run by top U.S. college students and earn management positions in your college years?

Then join us! We partner with Findingschool.net and have established the ?Finding Your Leaper Program?. As a Sales & Marketing Representative at the U.S. high schools, you would collaborate with top U.S. college students to carry out marketing plans, improve our services and gain first-hand exposure to the business world. 

Benefits:
1. Great resume boost for college application
2. Networking opportunities with college students from Harvard, Princeton, UPenn, Duke and many more!
3. Opportunities to show your leadership, marketing and business skills
4. A possibility to take management-level positions in college years
5. Rewards available from sales

Requirements:
1. A junior or senior in a U.S. high school
2. Outstanding performance in academic and extracurricular activities
3. Great communication skills
4. Responsible and able to meet time commitment (1-3 hours/week)
5. Ability to effectively reach out to targeted student populations

Responsibilities:
1. Design and execute a local marketing strategy with the goal of growing awareness and participation in Leap
2. Develop original content, including videos, stories, posters, and other multimedia assets to promote Leap
3. Other job duties as assigned

Deadline?January 25th?2013

How to apply?
Please write a short essay (less than 250 words) about why you want to join Leap and how you would contribute to our program. Please email your essay and your most recent academic transcript to leap.program.usa@gmail.com

After receiving your application, we will conduct phone interviews to qualified candidates. We would accept candidates on a rolling basis. Since the spots fill up quickly, please apply as soon as possible. The last day to apply is January 25th, 2013, but we are very likely to close our admission before then.

Please check more relevant information at: www.leap-usa.com
We are looking forward to speaking with you about your interests!



Leap Consulting Co.Ltd.
A Peer Mentor Program for International Students at U.S. High Schools
www.leap-usa.com
leap.program.usa@gmail.com

ID:100002209942621_622660121150980
Name:null
Story:N/A
Message:Today i walked into Teague and saw all the empty rooms and halls. I felt empty. Today was graduation. It's suppose to be a happy day, but somehow i felt sad.   I walked out of the global center after the econ commencement in a hurry without really saying good byes to my friends because i was tired. I didnt realize that this is one of the last few moments we will have together. In a couple of days, we would all depart. Although we all say "keep in touch" and "visit each other often", the ugly truth is that we probably wont. Its not that we dont value our friendship. Its that we are now going into the real world to start our new life and family, and itll be hard to sit back, relax, and reconnect with our old friends from our busy lives.  Throughout these four years, i made some great friends; some with annoying qualities haha. But today, when its time to depart, all i see and remember are the good times we had together, because thats wut really matters.  This last senior year has been crazy. I had so much fun! Thanks guys for a great year! These are the best times i had on college. I really hope that these days can last forever where we just drink and play random games. Thanks guys! Im not gonna wish u guys good luck for ur post graduation lives because i know you guys wont need it. Im gonna wish for us to be able to come back and relive our days together soon! <3

ID:100002813248009_454019568035147
Name:null
Story:N/A
Message:Today i walked into Teague and saw all the empty rooms and halls. I felt empty. Today was graduation. It's suppose to be a happy day, but somehow i felt sad.   I walked out of the global center after the econ commencement in a hurry without really saying good byes to my friends because i was tired. I didnt realize that this is one of the last few moments we will have together. In a couple of days, we would all depart. Although we all say "keep in touch" and "visit each other often", the ugly truth is that we probably wont. Its not that we dont value our friendship. Its that we are now going into the real world to start our new life and family, and itll be hard to sit back, relax, and reconnect with our old friends from our busy lives.  Throughout these four years, i made some great friends; some with annoying qualities haha. But today, when its time to depart, all i see and remember are the good times we had together, because thats wut really matters.  This last senior year has been crazy. I had so much fun! Thanks guys for a great year! These are the best times i had on college. I really hope that these days can last forever where we just drink and play random games. Thanks guys! Im not gonna wish u guys good luck for ur post graduation lives because i know you guys wont need it. Im gonna wish for us to be able to come back and relive our days together soon! <3

Message:A BIG thank you to all of you! The gold Coast tickets have been sold out so quickly, we couldn't have done so without your support. 

For those of you who have missed out, we have opened a waiting list in case anyone drops out. Also if you can't come with us anymore (none of us will want to let you go) please let us know ASAP so that we can contact members on the waiting list. 

For those who have paid their deposit, one of the event coordinators will contact you today to confirm your details, this is important as we will be providing these details to the airline, so please pick up our call/reply to our messages. 

Final payment is due THIS THURSDAY, please come to our office  or Coffee&Cake to finalise your payment. If you can't make it during our opening hours please contact us ASAP. 

Sorry for the long post, it is only with sufficient preparation that we can enjoy our Gold Coast Trip the most.

ID:100006641705075_712707735416524
Name:null
Story:Katrina Wertz posted an event to Facss China's timeline.
Message:This month of February, Carolina China Network is excited to present a discussion entitled China & Africa: Define the Relationship on Friday, February 28th from 4-5pm in Union Room 3206.  We are keen on exposing students on our campus to the myriad of reasons why China has turned attention to Africa?s continent and what opportunities and consequences have come about.  The short one-hour event will be a great chance to come together and eat free Chinese dumplings and discuss economic, diplomatic, and cultural collaborations from a high-level viewpoint.  Our goal is for each person in the room to hear, share, and learn something new about the Sino-Africa relationship that they may not have heard or considered before, and to meet someone in the room that you could continue the conversation with beyond this event!

    Jim Morgan  was named  President  and CEO  of Krispy  Kreme Doughnuts, Inc. in January 2008. Mr. Morgan has been a member of the Krispy  Kreme  Board  of Directors  since  2000  and was elected its Chairman in 2005.

 

    Mr. Morgan served as Chairman and CEO of Wachovia Securities following the acquisition of Interstate/Johnson Lane, Inc. (IJL) by Wachovia  Corporation.   He  also  served  as Chairman  and  CEO of Interstate/Johnson Lane, Inc.. Mr. Morgan is a past member of the Securities Industry Association Board of Directors and the New York Stock Exchange (NYSE) regional firms committee, and is currently on the Board of Directors of Coca-Coca Bottling Company Consolidated. Mr. Morgan has more than 40 years of business experience and is a

1969 graduate of Vanderbilt University. He also served as a lieutenant in the U.S. Navy.
